    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#gill1998"/><citedRange/></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>48.2049</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>088000</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><measure type="currency" unit="drachma">
                        <num value="1">
                            <expan><abbr><am><g type="drachma">𐅂</g></am></abbr>
                                <ex>δραχμά</ex></expan>
                        </num>
                    </measure>
                    <num type="cardinal" value="12">
                            <g type="acrophonic">Δ||</g>
                    </num>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>1 drachme la douzaine.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>1 drachma per dozen.</p> 
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>1 dracma alla dozzina.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>The lekanis was found broken into some 25 fragments between the last floor of the house and the ashy layer that covers a large part of the upper city and 
                also of the lower city and probably related to a destruction in the early fourth century.</p>
	<p>About this isolated instance of the Attic notation of a price through acrophonic numbers, see <bibl><ptr target="#cdl2017b"/>, p. <citedRange>200</citedRange>, footnote 50</bibl>.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
